Semiconductors are so integral to the history of Silicon Valley that they g=
ive the region its name, and, more importantly, its culture: chips require =
huge amounts of up-front investment, but they have, relative to most other =
manufactured goods, minimal marginal costs; this economic reality helped dr=
ive the development of the venture capital model, which provided unencumber=
ed startup capital to companies who could earn theoretically unlimited retu=
rns at scale. This model worked even better with software, which was perfec=
tly replicable.

That history starts in 1956, when William Shockley founded the Shockley Sem=
iconductor Laboratory to commercialize the transistor that he had helped in=
vent at Bell Labs; he chose Mountain View to be close to his ailing mother.=
 A year later the so-called =E2=80=9CTraitorous Eight=E2=80=9D, led by Robe=
rt Noyce, left and founded Fairchild Semiconductor down the road. Six years=
 after that Fairchild Semiconductor opened a facility in Hong Kong to assem=
ble and test semiconductors. Assembly required manually attaching wires to =
a semiconductor chip, a labor-intensive and monotonous task that was diffic=
ult to do economically with American wages, which ran about $2.50/hour; Hon=
g Kong wages were a tenth of that. Four years later Texas Instruments opene=
d a facility in Taiwan, where wages were $0.19/hour; two years after that F=
airchild Semiconductor opened another facility in Singapore, where wages we=
re $0.11/hour.

In other words, you can make the case that the classic story of Silicon Val=
ley isn=E2=80=99t completely honest. Chips did have marginal costs, but tha=
t marginal cost was, within single digit years of the founding of Silicon V=
alley, exported to Asia.

That story isn't true anymore, at least in terms of the chips that TSMC wil=
l be making in Arizona; packaging and testing is completely automated at th=
is point, which is to say it has the sort of economics that we associate wi=
th chips: huge amounts of up-front capital investment with effectively zero=
 marginal costs (primarily power). That in itself is its own lesson, howeve=
r: the real cost of moving packaging abroad ended up being that it was Asia=
 that moved the furthest down the learning curve in terms of the entire sem=
iconductor value chain, including the parts that Fairchild Semiconductor th=
ought they were keeping to themselves. Fast forward to today and TSMC can m=
ercy-build a packaging plant in Arizona, while still being firmly in contro=
l of the leading edge.

At the same time, this is also why I wouldn't immediately dismiss the role =
that potential tariff threats may have played in TSMC's expansion: U.S. fab=
s are more expensive thanks to significantly higher construction costs, whi=
ch has to be amortized across every chip, and also the relative weakness of=
 the Taiwan currency; tariffs, which are applied on a marginal basis (assum=
ing that the Trump administration applied them to finished goods, since mos=
t TSMC chips are integrated into systems somewhere other than the U.S.), un=
do both disadvantages (albeit by making chips more expensive as a category)=
.

Taiwan's Trump Card
-------------------

At the same time, you can also view this announcement with some amount of c=
ynicism, particularly given the lack of specificity about either timing or =
process. Consider this table of TSMC's Arizona announcements to date:

Announcement Pledge Process Current Target Actual Leading Edge May 2020 $12=
 billion 5nm 5nm 2024 2025 2nm Dec 2022 $28 billion 3nm 3nm 2026 Apr 2024 $=
25 billion 2nm 3nm 2028 Mar 2025 $100 billion 2nm

This isn't the most intuitive table I've ever created, but to clarify:

* *Announcement* is when a particular Arizona fab was announced; previous a=
nnouncements have been about one fab each, while today's is about three.
* *Pledge* is the incremental dollar amount TSMC is promising.
* *Process* is the announced process for the new Arizona fab.
* *Current* is the current leading edge process in Taiwan at the time of th=
e announcement.
* *Target* is when the Arizona fab was/is targeted to come online at the ti=
me of the announcement.
* *Actual* is when the Arizona fab actually came online.
* *Leading Edge* is the leading edge process in Taiwan at the time the Ariz=
ona fab actually comes online.

There is both an optimistic and a pessimistic way to look at this. On the o=
ptimistic side that first fab was upgraded to a more advanced 5nm node (TSM=
C calls it 4nm, but its the third-generation 5nm node); the second fab, mea=
nwhile, will also produce 2nm chips at some point in the future, although n=
ot in 2026. The best answer as to when, comes =E2=80=94 notably =E2=80=94 f=
rom the Taiwanese government. From CNA News in November ( https://focustaiw=
an.tw/business/202411290005 ) :

Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. (TSMC) will begin manufacturing its =
advanced 2 nanometer process in the United States in around 2028, according=
 to Wu Cheng-wen (=E5=90=B3=E8=AA=A0=E6=96=87), head of the National Scienc=
e and Technology Council (NSTC). When questioned by opposition Kuomintang (=
KMT) Ko Ju-chun (=E8=91=9B=E5=A6=82=E9=88=9E) at the Legislative Yuan Thurs=
day on whether TSMC will launch the 2nm process in the U.S. three years aft=
er it starts mass production in Taiwan in 2025, Wu said the timing is "more=
 or less" in 2028.

The three-year gap is significant because, according to local media, the NS=
TC and the Ministry of Economic Affairs have agreed that TSMC be only allow=
ed to invest in an advanced technology in a foreign country three years aft=
er mass production of the same process has begun in Taiwan.

Two months later the government seemed to be singing a different tune; from=
 the Taipei Times ( https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2025/01/1=
1/2003829992?s=3D31 ) in January:

Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co (TSMC, =E5=8F=B0=E7=A9=8D=E9=9B=BB), =
a major chip supplier to Nvidia Corp, would no longer be restricted from in=
vesting in next-generation 2-nanometer chip production in the US, the Minis=
try of Economic Affairs said yesterday=E2=80=A6Chipmakers were previously o=
nly allowed to produce chips using less advanced technologies, specifically=
 those that were at least two generations less advanced than those being us=
ed domestically, it said.

=E2=80=9CThose were old-time rules. Times have changed,=E2=80=9D Minister o=
f Economic Affairs J.W. Kuo (=E9=83=AD=E6=99=BA=E8=BC=9D) said on the sidel=
ines of a ministry media briefing yesterday. =E2=80=9CPrivate businesses sh=
ould make their own business decisions based on their own technological pro=
gress,=E2=80=9D Kuo said.

Well, fast forward to earlier today, and the Taiwanese government is back t=
o its original tune; from CNA News ( https://focustaiwan.tw/business/202503=
040014 ) :

Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. (TSMC) will not produce its most adv=
anced technologies in the United States in 2026, Economics Minister Kuo Jyh=
-huei (=E9=83=AD=E6=99=BA=E8=BC=9D) said Tuesday. Kuo made the comments dur=
ing an appearance at the Legislature, hours after the Taiwanese chipmaker a=
nnounced that it will invest an additional US$100 billion over the next fou=
r years to expand its manufacturing operations in the U.S.

Asked by Taiwan People=E2=80=99s Party lawmaker Chang Chi-kai (=E5=BC=B5=E5=
=95=93=E6=A5=B7) if TSMC would allow its most advanced technologies, the ye=
t-to-be-released 2 nanometer and 1.6 nm processes, go to the U.S. in the ne=
ar term, Kuo flatly denied it. TSMC recently opened its first U.S. factory,=
 which produces 4 nm chips, while construction on its second U.S. factory w=
ill only begin this year, he said. As for more advanced chips, =E2=80=9Cthi=
s is impossible,=E2=80=9D Kuo said. =E2=80=9CI guarantee it -- the 2 nm and=
 1.6 nm processes will not go to the U.S. next year.=E2=80=9D

TSMC is currently expected to begin mass production of 2 nm chips in Taiwan=
 in the second half of 2025, followed by 1.6 nm chips in 2026.

This is the pessimistic way of looking at that table above; my suspicion is=
 that the ultimate dates look something like this:

