nm 2030 2031 1nm 1.4nm 2nm 2032 2033 <1nm 1nm 2nm 2034 2035 <<1nm

In other words, I'm not sure that anything has changed, going as far back a=
s TSMC's original 2020 announcement. Once the company made the commitment t=
o Arizona it made sense to continue expanding its operations there, to gain=
 leverage on labor if nothing else. To that end, the company is on pace to =
build one fab for each process in the U.S., and that fab is going to be con=
sistently two processes behind Taiwan. Until TSMC says otherwise =E2=80=94 =
and again, yesterday's announcement was noticeably quiet in terms of proces=
ses and dates =E2=80=94 I don't think anything has changed.

And, I might add, there was this line from Kuo in that Taipei Times article=
 I linked above:

=E2=80=9CTrump will only be in office for four years and can=E2=80=99t run =
for another term so his impact will be limited,=E2=80=9D Kuo said.

That answer was, to be fair, in response to a question about wind power ( h=
ttps://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2025-01-10/taiwan-minister-says-trum=
p-s-impact-limited-by-his-single-term ) , but it's hard not to get the sens=
e that the sentiment colors all of the government's recent pronouncements. =
The fact of the matter is that Taiwan's single biggest trump card =E2=80=94=
 no pun intended! =E2=80=94 is TSMC; leading edge processes =E2=80=94 and, =
for that matter, leading edge R&D =E2=80=94=C2=A0will not be allowed abroad=
 so easily.

